title: Ned made significant structural and content changes
body:
Formed 4 main sections 1) original terminology definitions, 2) interpretation of terminology in RFC4949 specific to attestation 3) relevant background terminology in RFC4949, 4) other relevant background terminology not in RFC4949. 

A separate use cases section was created where the goal is not to define terminology but to capture high-level attestation use cases with emphasis on highlighting potential interaction or integration with other RFCs or working group defined technology. 

The section on attestation roles and conveyance architecture continues to use attestation architecture as a framework for introducing vocabulary. This is a departure from RFC4949 which is more of a dictionary format. I like having the architectural context. I don't know if it would make sense to also have an alphabetized listing of terminology for easy lookup. Alternatively, the architecture sections could focus on describing a reference architecture but assume the terms used are already formally defined.
